==Old English==
===Etymology===
From an earlier form ''*slehan'', from Germanic ''*slaxanan''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[slahan]] (Dutch [[slaan]]), Old High German [[slahan]] (German [[schlagen]]), Old Norse [[sla|slá]] (Swedish [[slå]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌻𐌰𐌷𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/slæ:an/}}

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''slēan'''}} (class VI strong: ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[slog|slōg]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[slogon|slōgon]]''', ''past participle'' '''[[slagen]]''')
# to [[beat]] or [[strike]]
# to [[kill]], especially violently; to [[slaughter]]
#:''slogan fram eastsæ oð westsæ ond him nænig wiðstod.''  They slaughtered from the east coast to the west and none withstood them.  (Bede)
# to [[slaughter]] an animal for food

===Derived terms===
*[[geslean|ġeslēan]]

